---
import { Picture } from "astro:assets"
import CaseStudy from "@/layouts/case-study.astro"
import { AspectRatio } from "@/components/ui/aspect-ratio"
import { getProject } from "@/data/projects"
import hourlyImg from "@/assets/projects/wheely-weather/hourly.png"
import specsImg from "@/assets/projects/wheely-weather/specs.png"
import weekImg from "@/assets/projects/wheely-weather/week.png"

const project = getProject("wheely-weather")!

const pictureFormats: ("avif" | "webp")[] = ["avif", "webp"]
const pictureWidths = [720, 1200]
const pictureSizes = "(min-width: 768px) 768px, 100vw"
---

<CaseStudy
  project={project}
  title="Wheely Weather"
  description="A cycling weather decision app that turns forecast data into a plain-language ride verdict, the best window to go, and the gear signals cyclists check before heading out."
  seoTitle="Wheely Weather · Cycling Weather Decision App"
  seoDescription="Wheely Weather is a cycling weather decision app that translates forecast data into ride-quality verdicts, hourly riding windows, and weather-based kit guidance."
>
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    Wheely Weather answers a near-term riding question: <em
      >can I ride right now, and if not, when?</em
    > The app leads with a verdict, then keeps the signals behind that verdict close
    enough for riders who want to check the call.
  </p>
  <p>
    The product is intentionally small. It focuses on the conditions that shape
    a bike ride: feels-like temperature, wind, gusts, rain chance, dewpoint, air
    quality, daylight, and alerts.
  </p>

  <h2>Project Frame</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Audience:</strong> cyclists making a near-term decision about whether
      conditions are worth a ride.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Surface:</strong> a responsive web app built for quick phone checks
      before leaving home.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Role:</strong> solo product strategy, UX/UI design, rating logic, front-end
      implementation, and launch.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Core product question:</strong> how might a weather app make the ride
      decision feel immediate without hiding the forecast data behind it?
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Problem</h2>
  <p>
    Before a ride, I was checking one weather app and falling back to another
    when the first came up short. The numbers were available, but the decision
    was not. A general-purpose forecast still left me asking whether the ride
    made sense.
  </p>
  <p>
    I talked with six riders I knew. The pattern was consistent: feels-like
    temperature matters more than the actual temperature, wind cancels more
    rides than rain, and the decision usually happens in the moment.
  </p>

  <h2>Research Signals</h2>
  <p>
    The research was intentionally lightweight. I was not trying to validate a
    large market; I was trying to understand the moment before a ride and the
    weather signals riders use to make that call.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Riders wanted a first-pass answer before studying the details.</li>
    <li>
      Wind and gusts carried more decision weight than standard weather apps
      implied.
    </li>
    <li>
      A single bad condition could override an otherwise acceptable forecast.
    </li>
    <li>
      When conditions were poor, riders still wanted to know whether a better
      window was coming later.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Product Goal</h2>
  <p>
    The goal was not to build another complete forecast. It was to turn forecast
    data into a decision path: tell the rider whether now is worth it, explain
    the reason, and point to the next useful opportunity when conditions
    improve.
  </p>

  <h2>Constraints</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      The app needed to make the first answer visible without hiding the raw
      weather signals.
    </li>
    <li>
      The rating model had to stay explainable, because riders disagree about
      wind, rain, heat, and what counts as “worth it.”
    </li>
    <li>
      Free weather and geocoding APIs shaped the data model, refresh behavior,
      and error states.
    </li>
    <li>
      The interface had to work at a glance on a phone before someone leaves the
      house.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Process</h2>
  <p>
    I started with the ride-planning behavior itself: what people check, what
    makes them cancel, and what they still want to know after a “no.” From
    there, I mapped the forecast inputs into a small set of ride-quality
    judgments and built the interface around the order a rider would naturally
    ask questions.
  </p>
  <p>
    The core flow became: verdict now, why it got that verdict, when it gets
    better, what to wear, and which day in the week is most promising.
  </p>

  <h2>Information Architecture</h2>
  <p>
    The screen order follows the decision sequence instead of the structure of a
    forecast API. The rider sees the verdict first, then the supporting
    conditions, then the time-based views that help them change plans.
  </p>

  <figure>
    <AspectRatio ratio={4 / 3}>
      <Picture
        src={specsImg}
        formats={pictureFormats}
        widths={pictureWidths}
        sizes={pictureSizes}
        alt="Ride Specs panel showing rain chance, feels-like temperature, wind, air quality, dewpoint, UV index, sunrise, and sunset."
      />
    </AspectRatio>
    <figcaption>
      Ride Specs keeps the forecast signals close to the verdict instead of
      burying them in a general forecast.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>Key Design Decisions</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>One verdict first.</strong> A five-level ride rating gives the first
      answer quickly: Great, Good, Fair, Poor, or Bad.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Worst factor, not average.</strong> A 90% rain day should not average
      out to “mostly fine.” For cycling, one bad condition can define the ride, so
      the verdict uses the weakest signal rather than smoothing it away.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Name what is wrong.</strong> When conditions are poor, the summary names
      the failing variable: heavy wind, rain, air quality, or another clear cause.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Show the next ride window.</strong> If now is bad but later improves,
      the app points to the better hour before asking the rider to study the chart.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Use color as a decision cue.</strong> The verdict card carries the rating
      color, so the first impression and the written call reinforce each other.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Keep the system adjustable.</strong> The rating logic stays visible
      in the interface and isolated in code, so future rider feedback can tune the
      model without redesigning the product.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <figure>
    <AspectRatio ratio={4 / 3}>
      <Picture
        src={hourlyImg}
        formats={pictureFormats}
        widths={pictureWidths}
        sizes={pictureSizes}
        alt="Hour-by-hour Wheely Weather panel with a ride-quality chart and a plain-language note about a rain window."
      />
    </AspectRatio>
    <figcaption>
      The hourly view lets a “no right now” turn into a specific ride window.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <figure>
    <AspectRatio ratio={4 / 3}>
      <Picture
        src={weekImg}
        formats={pictureFormats}
        widths={pictureWidths}
        sizes={pictureSizes}
        alt="Eight-day forecast view titled “The Week’s Wheelies,” with the best riding day highlighted."
      />
    </AspectRatio>
    <figcaption>
      When today is not promising, the week view highlights the day worth
      watching.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>Outcome</h2>
  <p>
    The shipped app replaced a scattered pre-ride check with one clear decision
    path: read the verdict, confirm the cause, and choose the next useful ride
    window. The first release also made the rating model easier to adjust,
    because every condition that can change the verdict is visible in the UI and
    represented in the front-end logic.
  </p>
  <p>
    The strongest product shift was moving weather from reference material to a
    recommendation. The app still exposes the underlying signals, but the first
    read is now framed around the rider’s actual question.
  </p>

  <h2>Tech</h2>
  <p>
    React 19, Vite, Tailwind CSS 4, Open-Meteo forecast and AQI data,
    OpenStreetMap/Nominatim reverse geocoding, the NWS API for U.S. weather
    alerts, and Cloudflare Pages. Vitest covers the rating logic because the
    verdict is the highest-risk part of the product.
  </p>

  <h2>Next Steps</h2>
  <p>
    The next pass is more rider testing before another threshold tune. I want to
    know how often riders disagree with the verdict, which condition caused the
    disagreement, and whether configurable weighting would make the product more
    useful without making the first answer less clear.
  </p>

  <h2>What I Would Revisit</h2>
  <p>
    The product now needs sharper feedback loops. A future version should let
    riders challenge a verdict in context, capture which signal felt wrong, and
    use that evidence to tune the thresholds without turning the interface into
    a settings-heavy weather tool.
  </p>
</CaseStudy>
